Inflation in Europe has slipped on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the price increase in the 13 euro area countries was higher than expected, after an inflation rate of 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 percent was recorded, said the European Community's statistics office located in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the U.S., U.K. and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the key interest rate by saying that falling interest rates, along with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment rates, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, this is Catch 22 for the ECB: "we must deter" inflation so that we no longer have to intervene on this subject later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 percent is a record over the past twelve years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
Cereal futures market ratings increased by 88 percent and soybean prices also reached their highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world oil price rose 52 percent, and last month, a barrel of black gold cost nearly $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, over the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut the key interest rate twice in 2008.
Gallup indicates a government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) has increased significantly at the beginning of December, with the largest number of supporters since 2002, while Gallup (Survey Institute) has never seen such a low level of socialist support, i.e. 13 percent.
For loyal voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of opposition voters, a support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) against the support of one-fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two percent throughout the population.
On loyal voters certain to go and vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate continued to deteriorate from the previous lowest point, the proportion of those who considered the country's economic situation to be particularly serious has never been higher, it stands at 41 percent and according to 46 percent complementary the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic outlook of last spring and summer, families are once again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population anticipates a worsening and only a tenth anticipates an improvement in the situation.
Last December, 71 percent of those surveyed, a majority never seen in Gallup’s previous polls, said the prime minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of the respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsny while 38 percent support Viktor Orban.
54 percent do not trust the prime minister at all and 27 percent do not trust the president of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of the change in the political situation is the proportion of society that thinks that discontent with the Prime Minister can be dealt with without a change in government.
While after the riots last October, 35 per cent of respondents wanted the government and the Prime Minister to remain in office, currently this rate is only 20 per cent, with the relative majority (33 per cent) believing that holding new elections would be the solution to this situation.
When asked about the intention to vote, 60 per cent of respondents said they would certainly vote and the additional 20 per cent said they would probably vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election to be held next Sunday", only 55 percent of respondents would certainly participate and another 15 percent would probably participate.
74 percent of people would say no to higher education tuition, 79 percent would say no to consulting fees, and 84 percent would say no to hospital fees.
When we look only at the same proportions among those who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters respectively would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital fees.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by nearly twenty percent
The hypermarkets located in the commercial triangle of Buda?rs maintained the average price increase of 16 percent from last year, with the difference that this year the VAT rate has not increased.
Article by Napi Gazdasag (Daily Economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budars, the usual daily Christmas Basket also increased by 16 percent on average, a value increase well over a thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
Prices, “which had already soared” in major grocery stores last December, have not risen sharply compared to the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The Daily Basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded by 91 forints, at least, the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value in the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
Prices of Unicum and live fish have remained at almost the same level as last year, however prices of turkey fillet, walnut and poppy have risen sharply.
In the stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, at Auchan, bread of one kilo was found at 139 forints only.
The competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was amazing to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the returnable two-liter bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the returnable bottle included.
However, this year, in terms of Daily Basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its Daily Basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased it by about 18 and 18 percent respectively.
Comparing last year’s most expensive shopping cart with this year’s cheapest shopping cart, we see a gap of 12 percent while the difference between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive shopping cart is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year, prices rose by an average of 1,206 forints, knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already noticed in last year’s Christmas prices.
This process has puzzled trade, hypermarkets could not visibly determine what margin to apply on products as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the turnover of a product, he risks losing a big profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
As a result of the change in the VAT rate, the price increase in the Daily Basket has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints higher than the value of 2006 when the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive since the value of the most expensive basket was 1,630 forints higher than last year and the prices of the cheapest one increased by 1,284 forints as well.
By approaching the two Christmas seasons, we have seen a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumer items have increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm the KSH data: for some basic supplies, the statistics institute found a price increase of more than 30 percent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and egg.)
According to the Daily Basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by barely more than 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers are in a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to get multinationals to accept the sudden increase in prices as well.
In the commercial golden triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
Based on our experience, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long shelf life foods in pallets.
On Wednesday morning important queues were formed at the checkouts of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, the turnover is less important in the province, many multinationals complain to the survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer items.
Many hospitals save money on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the incorrect use of antibiotics, have been registered in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overwork of medical staff do not help to block infections, says the chief doctor of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals are also saving on disinfectants
Not long ago, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of Jonos Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected in a man hospitalized following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured man in a serious car accident left the hospital, but soon after he had to return because of an MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have not been able to perform a major operation on him because of the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10, this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multidrug-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Borcz, chief medical officer of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Namely that it is the number of infections caused by a multidrug-resistant pathogen that has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
A third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without it developing a disease.
Infections caused by AS (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which reacts well to antibiotics, will develop a bacterium that is well resistant to antibiotics and will proliferate quickly in poor hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, on elderly, small weight or with a weakened body.
According to the head doctor of the hospital, there is nothing special in MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
We must not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only where we do not look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
“These patients are isolated, the healthcare staff put on rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics adapted to treat them,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, however the infection can not always be avoided.
Sample collection is not in fashion
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSAs could be prevented, but the current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not favourable to prevent the development and proliferation of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Borecz.
As this infection is most prevalent in hospitals and seniors' residences, hospitals should monitor inpatients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these examinations.
Most cases only emerge if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief medical officer of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has rigorous recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are Hungarian guidelines also for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, in other words microbiological examinations should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in ambulatory and basic care, Karolina Boercz said.
Many hospitals save money on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks, but important gaps are also detected in hospitals in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and by contact; however, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other while in terms of epidemic, the patients should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, are saving on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many sick people, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Barcz.
In hospitals where preventive measures are followed, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenses for social security funds, which is why this infection is being combated everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections are showing a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has identified the prevention of the incidence of multidrug-resistant pathogens (such as MRSA) as one of its priorities, as well as the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The commissioner, who had a fatal accident, was not intoxicated.
The official report of the fatal accident caused by the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement has been drawn up.
It can be ruled out that the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement, resigning from his post since, who crushed a pedestrian by causing his death last Tuesday, would have driven in a state of drunkenness or dizzy, said Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman of the Public Ministry of the capital after the relative observation has been established.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation, which has already found that the former commissioner did not consume alcohol before driving.
Last Tuesday, the former chief of the police station of the 22nd arrondissement crashed a 55-year-old man who was in front of him when he turned, with his personal car, in the street Kossuth Lajos of the 22nd arrondissement.
(Indeed, the fact that it crossed the road outside the pedestrian crossing is not a mitigating circumstance, according to the Highway Traffic Act a car that starts a turn must allow pedestrians to pass.)
The pedestrian died after being transported to the hospital.
Following this accident, the commissioner resigned his post and he asked for his retirement because, according to the police communication, this accident upset him a lot.
The investigation into this case is being carried out by the Prosecutor's Office in Budapest.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former commissioner cooperated from the beginning with the magistrates in charge of conducting the investigation.
EUR 400 million for infrastructure
On Friday, Hungarian Finance Minister Jonos Veres and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three agreements worth a total of 400 million euros for a line of credit to support education, transport infrastructure and the environment, as well as energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for Hungarian budgetary financing of transport and environment projects to be implemented from the Cohesion Fund, for which the parties have already signed a credit agreement worth EUR 100 million, this time for the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit agreement also concerns the budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, with the remaining EUR 150 million to be used later, following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a 50 million euro contract for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope in the first place as part of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the Metro Line 4 project was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would re-discuss the possible modification of the initial contract when Hungary has finalized the details of the funding of the metro with the EU.
According to Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has provided a total of EUR 8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its loans at the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and without a commitment fee.
Bulgaria, paradise of the EU real estate market
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of all Europe is turned to this Balkan country little mentioned in the past.
What, or who bought in this EU market which is always the cheapest but which will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most fashionable target of Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and cheap seaside houses.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albéna, the "Golden Sands", the "Sun Coast", the old Sozopol and Nessebar but they are more and more looking for a building in the area of Kavarna and Balcik too.
According to analysts from Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also arouse the interest of investors and they are also more and more to buy in the very cheap corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, also offers attractive opportunities, with retail and office spaces promising the highest amortization rate.
Bulgaria is on the best path to becoming one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus be a priority destination, after the summer season and winter season, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are at the same time looking to change their lives, their way of life.
Most of the buyers are English but others are coming from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the edge of the Black Sea and in the most famous ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who intend to settle buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging between 50 and 100 thousand euros, or old dilapidated houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, proximity to a big city, shops and in general that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of second homes (since last December, Bulgaria is listed among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is made up of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving medium- or long-term capital gains.
The price of buildings in the capital is constantly increasing due to an increasing demand.
In the European Union, property prices are the lowest in Bulgaria; however, in the last 5 years they have risen by 21 percent each year.
The increase in real estate prices essentially exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the Hungarian Six Percent
According to the statement by Environment and Water Minister Gobor Fodor, the meetings of the professionals will end on Tuesday, however, Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap, which is supposed to define the efforts to be made after the period of reduction of emissions defined by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
At the moment, there are intense discussions on this subject between developing and developed countries.
The United States also reported that, for the time being, it did not want to discuss exact figures, while it was ready to sign an agreement on reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 percent from 1990 levels until 2020.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries commit themselves, apart from emission reductions, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also signed on aid to be provided to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a 16-member board, probably under the United Nations Global Environment Fund (GEF), Piac es Profit (Market and Profit).
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister of the Environment and Waters Gobor Fodor confirms the EU's ambition to maintain its role as flagship in global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, regardless of the successful signing of the “Post-2012 Agreement”, and is ready to reduce them by up to 30 per cent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries are also ready to make commitments that are appropriate to their responsibility and capacity.
Fodor recalled that in 1997, the countries that signed the Kyoto Protocol had targeted a total reduction of 5.2 per cent and all 15 EU members at that time made the commitment 8 per cent less.
Hungary has made a commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to the level of the period between 1985 and 1987, our country will fulfill its commitment, recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within the interval of two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, the commitments of reduction below the values provided for in the Kyoto protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international system of emission reduction whose need was emphasized in the new report of IPCC, the international body responsible for climate change.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and the increase of the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 degrees celcius could no longer be avoided which, according to the scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
UK army recruits on YouTube
British Army units are sharing footage from their operations in Iraq and Afghanistan on the video-sharing site in an effort to make themselves popular.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) is passionate about YouTube: special units operating in Afghanistan upload video footage of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC said.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are checked at the Air Force Operations Headquarters in Kandahar and they are then transferred to London where the compatriots load them onto the Internet.
The political message is inescapable
Air force soldiers have already spent 139 sequences on the net by this route and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence signed up as the "Defencehead Quarters" in the spring of 2007 and released videos about operations in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the initial objective of the air force, the videos were spent on the net to recruit, and according to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to inform the general public of the real objectives of the army's presence abroad.
The propaganda published in this way costs virtually nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements on television, told the BBC Gordon Mackenzie, defence consultant, but it also inevitably carries a political message since it justifies in a special form the validity of military operations decided by the government.
The Americans made a game.
The army is bothered because, apart from the videos composed and censored carefully, amateur videos are passed on the sharing site which also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in the “official” propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
By the way, many videos had already been made on the net showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were carried out on real missions, but the British army has only recently been racing for the loading of these videos.
The Americans do the recruiting a little differently by using the shooting game America's Army for free. In this game the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers as part of a simulation more or less real.
