The forces of the mega-strike are gathering
The trade unions of the League and the National Association of Workers' Councils will constitute, Friday, their strike commission which will be responsible for coordinating the strike for an indefinite period of Monday.
On Saturday, a general assembly of protest will be held and on Monday, the day of the final vote on the law on health funds, the strike will begin.
This action will certainly cause significant traffic jams because rail traffic will be stopped almost completely and the employees of BKV (public transport company) will also strike until 1pm.
The unions of the league will make known, Friday afternoon, the details of their strike Monday, organized with the National Association of Workers' Councils.
The strike commission of LIGA - MOSZ will also be constituted, it will serve as coordinator of Monday's actions.
On Saturday, a general assembly of protest will be held and, from Monday, organizations joining the strike will stop work indefinitely if they fail to reach an agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, from the day of the vote in parliament on the law on health funds, is not defined.
If the National Assembly does not adopt the law on health insurance funds, the trade unions will immediately withdraw the call for a strike.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide on the next step.
According to Monday's agenda of the National Assembly, it is likely that the vote on the law on health funds will take place only late at night, or even at night.
Due to the strike scheduled for Monday, important traffic jams are planned: the railways will stop work for an indefinite period and during the morning part of the public transport in Budapest and more than half of the Volon companies are at risk of being stopped.
At the same time, at different points in the country, half the road will be blocked as well.
Many trade unions and civil organizations have joined the call for strikes, the list of which is constantly updated on the League’s website.
Some organizations report going on strike for an indefinite period, others have declared a temporary stoppage of work.
Until Thursday afternoon, the MV (Hungarian Railways) and the Free Union of Railway Workers (VDSZSZ) failed to reach an agreement on minimum services, but as the Christmas holidays approach, more and more people are taking the train.
According to the current communications, Budapest public transport will strike from the start of service until 1pm, Budapest airport between 7am and 9am, the Industrial Electricity and Thermal Energy Unions of the League will strike for four hours, the Teachers’ Union and the Democratic Teachers’ Union have called to strike for 2 hours and from 2am to 8am respectively.
The National Association of Physicians will strike across the country alternately, the Health and Social Workers Union (EDDSZ) attached to the SZEF will hold a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands, made by the League, requires the government to withdraw its proposal on health reform and submit a new conception to social debate.
The second claim requires that the new method of calculating retirement to be introduced from next year be introduced in several stages.
The third demand is for a guarantee, in terms of retirement before the legal age, which would make it possible to bring into the system the functions that deserve it before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is the rejection by the Free Union of Railway Workers (VDSZSZ), attached to the Unions of the League, of the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport concerning the secondary railway lines and the expectation of another proposal.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increased country risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital (Risk Analysis Division), the activity of the Hungarian Guard, set up last August, with the support of Jobbik Magyarorszegert Mozgalom (Movement for a Better Hungary) increases, in several aspects, the political risk of Hungary and the region.
In its “risk warning”, the company points out that, in relation to the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is already that “in the short term aggressive ethnic clashes can occur following the aggravation of the already existing ethnic tension between the gypsy and non-gypsy population of Hungary”.
The research institute added that the Hungarian Guard’s political strategy likely aimed at provoking this situation is the main reason for this.
As they say, this is due to one of the main shortcomings of Hungarian political actors: “public actors have passed the public debate on the Roma case to representatives of radical and extreme political groups who have based a political strategy on the dispute between Gypsies and Hungarians”.
The problem is compounded, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are strengthened, and aggressive conflict is more likely to occur, they say.
However, according to the research institute, under the effect of the increased attention of the Hungarian and international media the activity of the Hungarian Guard "has significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, especially regarding confidence in the stability and democratic maturity of the country".
They recall that, following greater publicity given to the reorganization of Hungarian radical and far-right groups since autumn 2006, many associations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007 calling themselves the "National Association of Self-Defense".
“The common feature of these gatherings is that they define themselves as a civil organization while they publicly declare the preparation of their members for defense missions (catastrophes, national defense, defense of order), armed if necessary, moreover, by evoking the incapacity of the police, the army, in other words the state,” they added.
They pointed out that everything happened according to the method which, based on the resentment of the political and party society, seeks to disguise different political ambitions under a civilian aspect.
The emphasis on civility and association status therefore serves only to avoid the legal pitfalls of registering these associations in court, but they are also a political strategy.
The analysis points out that the activity of the Hungarian Guard is a factor that also increases the risk in relation to neighbourhood relations.
