The party is not marked in red everywhere
In Hungary, the law defines exactly the days of celebration and, around the holidays, it has become common to reorganize the working days whose number will decrease next year.
Holidays are not uniform in the EU and the US either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes between national and state holidays as well as rest days.
Rest days are often linked to religious holidays or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the New Year, the last day of the year that ends and the first day of the New Year are also days of rest, the latter all the more so that the revelers can rest quietly.
In one year, we have a total of eleven holidays marked in red.
March 15 is a national holiday, commemorating the 1848 revolution, as is October 23 which is also the 1956 revolution memorial day.
On August 20th, we celebrate the constitution of our state, May 1st is Labor Day and on November 1st and 2nd, we remember our family members and friends who have passed away.
In addition, we have two days at Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
The days of our state, national or religious holidays rarely falling on a weekend, according to the calendar, it has become common to reorganize the working days in cases where there is only one working day left before or after the holiday marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price of extended weekends by working or going to school on the Saturday before the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has ruled in a special regulation on the days of replacement before or after the holidays.
The law extends to all employers and to all their employees, to civil servants and to persons working in the public service.
It does not, however, apply to service societies, to institutions operating without interruption and in service, because of their vocation, and also for days of rest.
This year, working days will be changed only around the end of the year holidays: from December 24, life stops almost all over the country because according to experiences the majority of people do rather overtime or take holidays that they have saved for these purposes to be able to spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day at home.
Next year many holidays fall in the middle or end of the week, so there will be fewer changes in workdays compared to this year.
The calendar will be reorganized for the first time around Labor Day to allow employees to stay at home four days in a row.
Saturday 25 April will be a working day to have a day off on Friday 2 May.
Another change is scheduled for October 23: Saturday, October 18 will be a working day replacing Friday, October 24.
On the other hand, next year, the end of the year is announced under the sign of the holidays because from December 24, everyone will have a non-stop break even if the day of the new year falls on a Wednesday.
