State Debt Will Rise to a Trillion in 2009
The burden of a state debt exceeding 84,000 kroner falls on each Czech.
Total debt rose to 842.7 billion crowns at the end of September.
The government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion crowns this year.
As a result of better-than-expected changes in the savings from the state budget, the department reduced the planned amount to 152.8 billion kroner.
The state debt of the Czech Republic rose towards the end of September to 842.7 billion kroner.
During the nine months of this year it has therefore increased by 40.2 billion kroner.
However, from June onwards, it has fallen by 13.4 billion kroner.
Today, the Ministry of Finance has confirmed its data on the state debt dating back to early October.
The burden of a debt exceeding 84,000 kroner falls on each Czech Republic.
Over the past year, the state has been in debt for more than 111 billion kroner.
"For now, it seems that, thanks to a smaller deficit forecast for next year, we could exceed the border by a trillion kroner only in 2009.
Next year, the debt is expected to be between 900 billion and 1 trillion kroner," Patria Finance analyst David Marek told iHNed.cz.
The forecast of Next Finance analyst Vladimor Pikor is similar: "We could exceed the trillion in the course of 2009.
The exact date will depend on the next budget that is not yet known.
If it turns out that the situation on the political scene is changing, that policies are ready to save more, the date could be pushed back to 2010.
But I don’t expect that change,” he said.
Debts are growing
The debt of the State is constituted by the debts of the central government and it is generated essentially by the accumulation of the deficits of the State budget.
The state debt is financed by treasury bills, annuity bonds, direct loans or, for example, by loans from the European Investment Bank.
The domestic debt of the State has increased this year from 38.5 billion crowns to 719.4 billion crowns.
The external debt of the state has increased this year for the time being from 1.7 billion crowns to 123.3 billion crowns.
The debt of the so-called negotiable state reached at the end of September 803.3 billion crowns and from June it decreased by 13.7 billion crowns.
The average debt liability of the state amounted to 6.5 years.
“Total debt increased interannually from the first to the third half of the year by 13 percent, which is, given the current good health of the economy, a figure far too high.
It is interesting that the increase is generated mainly by pension securities where it reaches 20 percent.
It is bad that the debt is growing, but on the other hand it indicates that there will be something to negotiate when the pension reform comes,” commented the data Pikora.
Better than expected
It follows from the strategy of financing and managing the state debt for the year 2007 that the government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion crowns this year.
However, at the beginning of September, thanks to a better-than-expected evolution of the state budget savings, the Ministry reduced the planned amount to 152.8 billion kroner.
The sum is essentially constituted by the deficit of the state budget which will obviously reach 76 billion crowns this year, instead of the 91.3 billion crowns initially planned.
Secondly, these are the maximum sources planned for the Czech Consolidation Agency, namely 13.3 billion crowns, the reserve of 10 billion for the payment of pensions, the financing of state pension securities for 43 billion crowns and the repayments of loans from the European Investment Bank amounting to 1.8 billion crowns.
