A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are freely accessible.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of linear in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were up to now only available for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or his successors.
The eleven states in charge of their management – including Germany, France, Israel and the United States – agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
As the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
Historians’ access to Bad Arolsen will allow them to carry out research “in particular on the movements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of forced workers,” says Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, were opposed to the opening to the public of these nominative documents, because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the supposed homosexuality or the mental disability of some of the victims of the deportation.
The registers of the concentration camps or arrest warrants drawn up by the Gestapo had been collected after the war with a practical aim: to find the civilians deported or subjected to compulsory work and, possibly, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,” said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Research on Antisemitism at the Technische Universitet in Berlin in 2006.
