These two worlds are almost the same size, with similar orbits, although Venus is closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, Venus might have had Earth-like conditions, and might even have been habitable.
But the greenhouse effect due to carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion due to solar radiation combined with slower rotation has led Venus to a whole other kind of evolution.
Today the planet is without water, is ravaged by hurricanes and lightning storms and has a temperature surface warm enough to melt lead.
The findings of Venus Express, the European Space Agency’s probe, which has been studying the planet for a year, offer a sad vision of Earth’s potential future due to catastrophic climate changes.
University of Oxford physics professor Fred Taylor, one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: “We are beginning to understand why Venus’ climate is so different from Earth’s, although the planets themselves are virtually similar.
“Our new data allows us to establish a scenario that billions of years ago, Venus would have been originally identical to Earth, perhaps even with a habitable surface.”
Enriched uranium sequestered by the police.
