In 1980 and 2000, a candidate united the party early and convincingly through a message of success on American greatness thus bringing leaders closer together.
This time, the party is divided and the result is far from clear.
The Pains of Labour
Gordon Brown discovered a new hole in which to sink; even if he resigned, the situation would not change.
Given the trend of British scandals, this one is not particularly juicy.
No decorations sold, no Parisian hotel bills from politicians, no extra conjugal finger sucked.
But now a revelation attests that a wealthy businessman would have masked for four years, under false names, his contributions to the current Labour Party, equivalent to more than $ 650,000 ($ 1.3m), which the party would not have declared: A new battle that Gordon Brown would have done well without.
Two months ago, the Prime Minister backtracked on his election plan, stupidly insulting British intelligence by proclaiming that opinion polls did not influence his decision, and that he hoped instead to offer a compact and effective government.
On the contrary, such as Vince Cable, the brilliant Liberal Democrat leader, said that the terrifying Mr. Brown turned from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The buyout of Northern Rock, a troubled bank on the brink of crack, demonstrated a breach of direction and poor judgment in an emergency.
Inadequate proposals to change the tax code have provoked a coalition of industry groups against the government.
The loss of 25 million personal data by tax authorities has revealed an incredible administrative blunder.
A trio of retired generals launched a revolt among the Lords, protesting against cuts in military spending: they proclaimed that being defense minister is for them, a part-time job.
At present, the suspicion of shady donations from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, the general secretary of Labor (and his ex-head of vigilance) have caused them to have to resign.
None of this means that Mr. Brown is inevitably heading out.
However, governments can come to a point where it would be impossible to govern.
People don’t like politicians, and don’t trust them, but usually leave their doubts aside when a new government comes to power.
It seems obvious that a Prime Minister cannot improve things, or even govern for a long time, when he risks suspension: the public administration is no longer functioning; the cabinets of ministers are taking stock; the press is looking for bad stories; and the government is becoming defensive and without any goals.
In one sense, Mr. Brown's position is particularly difficult, because unlike other political leaders, he can't brag about being a beginner.
Although he would like to repudiate Tony Blair, he was still his senior lieutenant.
The problems with Northern Rock and tax data, for example, are related to Mr. Brown's decisions when he was Chancellor of the British Treasury.
And even if he’s not directly involved in Blair’s misfortunes, such as the long investigation into party funds “cash for members of the House of Lords,” voters might think otherwise.
But Mr. Brown's difficult situation is not as tragic as it sounds.
The blunders are not so monstrous as the members of the Tory party make it seem.
As in Mr. Bean, there are no victims or scams.
And the remedy, though painful, could be to concretize Mr. Brown’s long-standing Stalinist tendencies, in favor of a reliable and slightly brutal government.
The new scandal over political donations is a good example.
Mr. Abrahams, a very peculiar figure, who compares his donations to charity, said he does not want any public recognition of his beneficence.
He may have his opinion, but it is not for him to decide.
The laws against the anonymity of big political backers are clear, and they exist for a good reason: The public has a right to know who is contributing to the success of those who will govern the country.
Mr. Watt, who said he was aware of Mr. Abrahams' programs, without knowing that it was illegal, will therefore have to be questioned, as will Jon Mendlesohn, the head of grant collections who spoke about the dubious donations in October.
But so far Mr. Brown is not involved: There is no indication that he was aware of these steps, even though most of the payments made were made following his arrival in government in June.
So far the Prime Minister has done half.
He quickly condemned his party's legislative loophole, but he did not draw attention to the fact that the decision-making power is based on something he knows well, using a committee of inquiry on this subject composed of a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the lessons to be learned are not complicated.
And if the law has been violated, it is the responsibility of the police.
In addition, there are many other things that Mr. Brown must do, such as find a permanent chair for the independent committee of the Standards of Public Life, without a leader for six months, and prepare a good reform on the financial of the political parties.
This would force the Labour Party, in a moment of weakness, to collaborate with the Tories, which could lead it to abandon its particular financial relationship with the confederations; in short, a bitter pill for a supporter such as Mr. Brown.
But he should face some partisan facts.
The Conservative party now has a good advantage in the election; it has two years to win back voters, and the only way to win is to demonstrate impeccable integrity and strong skills.
Card scams.
Would the mortgage crisis contaminate the U.S. credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, it is normal to see fins fanned, swirling around.
Now that the U.S. real estate market is going through a critical phase, predators are targeting the U.S. credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs believe credit card losses could reach $99 billion if contagion spreads from mortgages to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in the rates of fees and insolvency, which measures the parts of the balance sheet that are not recoverable or that are, more than 30 days later.
HSBC announced last month that it has taken $1.4 billion in consumer credit, in part due to weak cardholders.
It is too early to panic.
Costs and insolvencies are still moderate.
According to Moody, a tax agency, the third-quarter insolvency rate of 3.89% is almost a point lower than its historical average.
The deterioration in rates is partly explained by technical factors.
A 2005 U.S. change in personal bankruptcy laws caused a sharp drop in bankruptcy records, which in turn caused heavy credit card losses; the number of records (and thus insolvency rates) could increase even if borrowing conditions were to worsen.
The industry also announces fixed payment rates, which highlight the amount of monthly debt that consumers must pay.
and confidence in the security of credit card capital is quite strong despite the paralysis of other aspects of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research company, predicted that the volume of issuance for 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
The direct infection links between the mortgage crisis and the credit card market certainly exist: consumers may prefer to increase their debt now that fair mortgages have disappeared.
But card issuers are paying more attention to cash flow rather than the value of wealth, and so falling property prices have not necessarily led to a change in the credibility of borrowers.
They could even bring benefits to credit card issuers.
Premiums to consumers for paying mortgages fall if properties cost less than the value of the loan; therefore, credit card debt would become a priority to repay the whole.
Card issuers are able to respond much faster than mortgages and with more flexibility to such crisis conditions, as they can change interest rates or alter credit limits.
In theory, this should reduce the risk of a quick recovery.
“We’re not going to wake up one morning and revalue all the loans,” said Gary Perlin, the director of Capital One.
If a financial catastrophe in the credit card market is unlikely, there is a high risk of a significant decline.
If lower real estate prices and a contraction in the credit market bring America into recession, the industry will certainly face a macabre future.
Pay close attention to the dorsal fins.
The British bankers plead guilty to the Enron case.
The three British bankers who were to testify their roles in relation to a fraud committed by Enron's previous chief financial officer, Andrew Fastow, changed their statement, pleading guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew had initially declared themselves innocent of the seven charges of alleged collusive fraud in 2000, committed by Fastow in a secret financial scam in order to enrich themselves in spite of their employees.
They are expected to appear in court in January.
But during a hearing presided over by U.S. Judge Ewing Werlein Jr., they all found themselves guilty of committing fraud.
The three ex-executives of Greenwich NatWest, a subsidiary of the Royal Bank of Scotland PLC group, have become famous all over Britain because of the extradition proceedings that lasted two years.
In the United States, their case remains an open question for this investigation launched following the fall of Enron in 2001.
The charges against them in 2002 made it clear to Fastow that he was the subject of the government's investigation into the Enron debacle.
The accusations against the bankers, dubbed the "Natwest Three" claim to have come to Houston in 2000, to organize a fraudulent scenario with Fastow and his ex-right-hand man, Michael Kopper.
NatWest Greenwich invested in a subsidiary of an Enron partner controlled by Fastow, who was the director of many fraudulent scenarios, which helped him rig bankruptcy proceedings.
At the beginning of 2002, the bank had considered its interest in the subsidiary to be zero, but in fact the three British already know its value.
A company controlled by Kopper bought the interest of the subsidiary's bank for 1 million euros.
The bankers paid Kopper $250,000 as interest for this company.
According to the charge, Fastow falsely told Enron that the energy company was willing to pay $20 million to Greenwich NatWest for its shares in the subsidiary.
But in truth this $20 million went into the pockets of the British bankers, Fastow and others.
According to the charges, the bankers would have gotten $7.3 while Fastow, Kopper and the others would have earned $12.3 million.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to his active role in two conspiracies in the Enron debacle.
The British trio was arrested three months later.
Fastow endures a six-year incarceration in a federal prison in Louisiana.
Kopper is imprisoned for three years and a month in a prison in Texarkana.
The three Britons were released on bail of $1 million each, forcing them to live in the United States during the trial.
Enron, previously the seventh largest national company, bankrupted in December 2001 after years of accounting tricks, could no longer hide its billions of debt or even offer its bogus speculations as profitable.
The collapse caused thousands of layoffs, more than $60 billion in lost market value and more than $2 billion in loss for retirement plans.
Enron’s founder Kenneth Lay and ex-CEO Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year for their involvement in the company’s collapse.
Skilling was sentenced to more than 24 years in prison.
The charges against Lay for conspiracy, fraud and other offenses were unsuccessful because of his death due to a heart attack last year.
