The cost of a G550 Gulfstream aircraft, equipped with a Rolls-Royce engine and with sufficient fuel range to fly non-stop from Moscow to Los Angeles, starts at $54 million.
But this is only a small change for some Russians.
“It can carry up to 18 passengers,” said Dan Firer, a Gulfstream representative.
“Even if no one really needs that many seats since it’s more of a family-owned aircraft or for the president of a company.”
Mr. Firer was present at the Gulfstream stand last Friday, at the Millionaires’ Fair, a four-day consumer incentive orgy, which is held in a huge exhibition center around the capital.
In addition to Gulfstream, more than 200 other exhibitors were present with their stands, hoping to arouse the interest of the new rich Russians for their varied products, ranging from mahogany yachts to cars filled with diamonds like those of 50 Cent.
Mr. Firer was scrutinizing a bright orange Porsche, displayed next to his stand.
“It’s a nice car, but nothing like our product,” he said.
“After the United States, Russia is the second largest private aircraft market.”
“Thanks to an oil boom, the Russian capital seems to be rolling in black gold, like Dallas.”
“We experienced the same thing in the 1890s, when some Americans became so rich and landed in Europe where they were considered materialistic,” said Marshall Goldman, a senior Davis Department scholar of Russian and Eurasian studies at Harvard University.
Like the Saudis in the 1970s, the Japanese in the 1990s, the Russians emerge as the world’s biggest spenders.
The biggest luxury brands are looking for their place in the Klondike.
This week, at another location in Moscow, a conference on the luxury industry allowed Donatella Versace, Tom Ford and Bernard Arnault, president of LVMH, to exchange ideas on the strategy to follow for the sale of luxury goods to markets like Russia.
(The conference was organized by the International Herald Tribune, which is owned by The New York Times.)
Russia has 53 billionaires worth $282 billion, according to Forbes’ list of the richest people.
In addition, two-thirds of the rich are made up of 103,000 Russian millionaires who are worth $670 billion globally, according to a study on the evolution of personal wealth in the former Soviet Union, carried out by economists at the Center for Economic and Financial Research.
(The World Bank said that in 2005, 15.8% of Russians lived below the poverty line.)
