The show seems to be aimed primarily at the new rich, the kind of buyers of Russian brands willing to queue in the corks to come to a huge warehouse where are exposed Cadillac Escalades, platinum canives, ice creams, personalized pool tables, apartments in Dubai and teddy bears Gund.
The public could buy the tickets for 30 euros ($44.57).
“Russians are interested in defining the most expensive and best brands,” said Mr. Gijrath, sitting proudly at the Royal factory stand of Delf Dutch porcelain manufacturing, in front of a wall painting of Raimbrant on blue tiles, handmade.
“It’s clear that Russians are more interested in bling bling.”
Indeed, the sellers said here that Russians with old capital (10 to 15 years are too by Russian standards) have already switched from bright logos to a kind of limited edition brand that could not sell at the show.
Despite this, thousands of people, either millionaires, emissaries of millionaires or tourists, walk the exhibition every day.
Some even buy.
On the first night of the exhibition last Thursday, Roman Ershow, the CEO of King Koil beds, said he sold two sets of silk, cashmere, and cotton mattresses inlaid with gold threads.
On the first night, Mikhail Lyubiumov, the sales manager of A1 motorcycle, a company that equips cars with state-of-the-art alarm systems, also said he sold a Russian millionaire, the bright orange Porsche, for $170,000.
By Sunday afternoon, Andrei Karapetian, the president of L.A. Connection, a company that customizes luxury cars, said he would sell three wristband-like cars, for Rolls-Royce Phantoms, for $55,000 each.
He showed a reporter, the wheel of a car designed for the owner of a Russian casino, who wanted it to be inlaid with Swarovski crystals to make it look like a roulette wheel.
The set of four costs $22,000.
“The Russian millionaire who wants wheels made of ostrich leather, or a photo of his wife made of cubic zirconium, will not necessarily drive with such tires,” Karapetian said.
He will certainly keep it in his garage already containing 30 or 40 vehicles.”
Even though many of his Russian clients are wealthy, Karapetian said the phrase “Russian millionaire” is not on the agenda, given the rise in real estate prices here.
