Everyone hopes that the Federal Reserve will lower rates related to the effervescence of the world stock market.
Shares were blown up on both sides of the Atlantic yesterday, after the market hoped that the Federal Reserve would try to calm credit conditions, later reducing interest rates promoted by the soothing statements of the vice president of the US central bank.
Stock markets are exploding in London, New York and all over Europe after Donald Kohn, No. 2 after Ben Bernanke, chairman of the Federal Reserve, said that those who decide, must be “flexible and pragmatic” in their actions in the turbulent financial markets.
In a clear effort to reassure irritable markets in light of these new credit-related tensions, Kohn said the recent turmoil has partly “reversed some improvements in market functioning in late September and October.
Should this severe turbulence persist, it would increase the likelihood of further rigidity of financial conditions for owners and businesses, he said.
These comments appear to investors as a clear signal that the Federal Reserve is ready to inject new capital into U.S. markets, and that further cuts in interest rates could stabilize credit conditions.
These remarks also helped calm Wall Street down with even worse news about the U.S. economy, such as the biggest drop in home sales for the month of October.
