It's not Warhols' coffers.
The one who connects the concepts of Sweden and wooden case, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, Swedish-made wooden crates are casting shadows on Warhol’s list of works.
A large part of the ninety Brillo-Boxes of "Stockholm Type" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" doubted the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes a few months ago, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm today leads to a disillusioning result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", of which the former director of the museum Pontus Hulten gave a gift in 1995 to the Moderna Museet, are copies - as well as a large "Box"
Ancient history is entangled, a disconcerting web of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created in New York his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted wooden boxes, which are based on the red-blue-white design of the soap cartons powder "Brillo".
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 - with the agreement of Warhol - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been directly delivered from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden crates in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time speak today of about fifteen wooden crates that at the time would have entered right into the history of art and auctions, as the original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol authorized, with the name "Stockholm Type".
Some of them have reached over $100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén museum later falsely claimed that about a hundred wooden crates had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would then have ceded to him.
In truth, the 105 cases of Hultén were produced in Malma in 1990 only, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Bystrom, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, alongside the museum’s six Brillo-Boxes, three other Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and sanded, then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The texture of the copies that date from the year 1990 reveals on the contrary that the paint was directly applied without a bottom layer on the laminated panels, using a roll of paint - moreover it is not an oil painting, but an acrylic.
"These crates have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of the Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol," suggests the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six crates in its collection as copies/material."
Already in July the Authentication Board has of course announced that it will investigate the "heavy accusations" that will be raised in the case of the boxes of soap powder.
But since then, there has been an inexorable silence.
Rebel Soldiers in Manila Abandon
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers give up, the same ones who had entrenched themselves in a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who blamed the President for corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters in the hotel that he could not answer for any bloodshed.
The soldiers loyal to the government had shortly before stormed the hotel with tear gas.
The two dozen soldiers had been entrenched for hours in the building.
About half of them were standing in court Wednesday due to a failed coup attempt in 2003 – among them Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly eclipse himself with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police, who normally had to watch over them, had apparently deserted in his favor and joined his mutiny.
They broke into the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the removal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Troops loyal to the government closed the area around the respectable hotel.
The President convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the actions of the soldiers.
“People have had enough,” Trillanes said.
“We call on people to join us.”
Gen. Danilo Lim, who was in command before the elite unit of the Scout Rangers, said other army units soon wanted to join the march.
Critics of the regime had called for a major demonstration against the President on Wednesday.
His government has been surrounded for months by accusations of corruption.
The financial district of Manila was already since 2003 the scene of the attempted mutiny of about 200 members of the army against Arroyo.
The uprising broke out nearly 24 hours after the army refused to join.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
